{"title":"Config loader: sync read tradeoff","gitnotes":1,"type":"text","body":"Rationale note for reviewers.\n\nWe chose synchronous fs.readFileSync over async loadConfig because:\n- The demo CLI exits immediately after one command; no event loop reuse.\n- Keeps the call stack shallow for screenshot diffs (single await-free path).\n- Matches how many internal tools load ~/.config/*.json at startup.\n\nDownside: blocks the main thread on large files. Acceptable for demo; production fork should switch to fs.promises.readFile with a timeout guard.\n\nNon-obvious: missing file returns DEFAULT_CONFIG, not an error — see loadConfig catch block. That surprised me in review; document in README (commit 30)."}
